Because alignment can only be measured at a shared level of granularity, word-level embeddings serve as the natural input to the optimization objective. For each source-language word embedding $\mathbf{u}_i$ and target-language word embedding $\mathbf{v}_j$, we compute pairwise cosine similarity $s_{ij} = \mathbf{u}_i^\top \mathbf{v}_j / (\|\mathbf{u}_i\| \|\mathbf{v}_j\|)$. Cosine similarity is appropriate here because it is invariant to embedding magnitude, isolating directional proximity as the signal for semantic overlap [CITATION]. A pair is retained as a candidate alignment only if $s_{ij} \geq \tau$, where $\tau = 0.85$ is set to suppress low-confidence correspondences that would otherwise inject noise into subsequent optimization. This threshold is not arbitrary: preliminary experiments confirmed that alignments below this value produce statistically unreliable transfer targets [CITATION]. The resulting filtered alignment set constitutes the structural prior on which the transfer layer depends — and it is precisely this prior that makes the weight initialization in §3.3 a principled operation rather than an unconstrained one.</draft>

